2
Agenda
• Welcome from the U S  Department of Education, Office of Career,
Technical, and Adult Education (OCTAE)
• About Ability to Benefit (ATB)
• Overview of Technical Assistance (TA) Opportunity
• Q&A
• Important Dates
3
Welcome
Erin Berg
Program Specialist and Contracting Officer’s Representative
U S  Department of Education
Office of Career, Technical, and Adult Education (OCTAE)
4
About DEAL
• Funded by OCTAE under Contract No  GS10F0201T 
• Aims to support the development of ATB alternate state processes
and increase the overall usage of ATB to support the dual enrollment
of adult learners in postsecondary education
• Staffed by MSG, World Education, and RTI International
5
Poll: Who’s Here?
Please indicate your organization type:
• State adult education agency
• State higher education agency
• Higher education institution
• Local adult education provider
• Other (please enter in chat)
6
About ATB
Presenters: Sandy Goodman and Alexis Cherewka, World Education
7
What is ATB?
ATB alternatives allow students who do not have a high school
diploma or equivalency to become eligible for Title IV student
assistance (federal student aid) if the student is enrolled in an eligible
career pathway program (ECPP) 
8
ATB Timeline
9
ATB Student Eligibility
• Students who seek Title IV eligibility under ATB alternatives, must:
• Be enrolled in an ECPP
• Have the opportunity to attain a high school equivalency -
underscoring the importance of dual enrollment in both adult
education and the postsecondary career pathway
• Be eligible for federal student aid
Note: Paraphrased from (GEN-24-08) Ability to Benefit State Process and Eligible Career Pathways Programs, Dear
Colleague Letter, June 12, 2024
10
ATB Student Eligibility (continued)
• Students must also meet one of the following ATB eligibility
alternatives:
• Pass an ATB test (CELSA, ACCUPLACER, Texas Success Initiative
Assessment)
• Complete at least six credit hours or 225 clock hours applicable to
a degree or certificate offered by the postsecondary institution
• Participate in a state process approved by the Secretary of
Education
Note: Paraphrased from (GEN-24-08) Ability to Benefit State Process and Eligible Career Pathways Programs, Dear
Colleague Letter, June 12, 2024
11
ECPPs
• Students must be concurrently enrolled in all three of the following:
• Adult education and literacy programming that assists adults in
attaining a high school diploma or equivalent,
• A Title IV eligible postsecondary program, and
• Workforce preparation activities and training for a specific
occupation or occupational cluster 
Note: Paraphrased from (GEN-24-08) Ability to Benefit State Process and Eligible Career Pathways Programs, Dear
Colleague Letter, June 12, 2024
12
ECPPs (continued)
• ECPPs must also:
• Align with the skill needs of the state or regional economy
• Include academic and career counseling
• Accelerate students’ educational and career advancement
Note: Paraphrased from (GEN-24-08) Ability to Benefit State Process and Eligible Career Pathways Programs, Dear
Colleague Letter, June 12, 2024
13
Why Implement a State Process?
• Students don’t have to wait until they can pass a test or earn six
credits 
• Students and colleges don’t have to find funds for test fees or the
first six credits 
• State processes can help create and support an intentional adult
dual enrollment strategy 
• States don’t have to commit all institutions to implementing the state
process when applying 
• Colleges in states with an approved process have more options – they can also use other two ATB options (i e , states and institutions
are not limited to one ATB alternative) 
14
States with Approved State Processes
● California
● Illinois
● Iowa
● Minnesota
● Mississippi
● Washington
● Wisconsin
States that have or recently had an approved state process 
15
Promising Practices of Adopters
A landscape scan identified three interconnected themes of adopters
and their partners:
• Intentional and sustained systems that allows adopters to
effectively identify, enroll, support, and track both potential and
current ATB students 
• Clear and collaborative partnerships that are driven by a shared
vision and sense of collective responsibility 
• A learner-centered mindset driven by the belief that adult
learners can succeed in postsecondary education without a high
school equivalency 
16
Resources
► (GEN-24-08) Ability to Benefit State Process and Eligible
Career Pathway Programs
This Dear Colleague Letter explains changes made to the
ATB State Process regulation at 34 § 668 156 and the
addition of regulatory requirements for Eligible Career
Pathway Programs (ECPPs) at 34 CFR § 157 
https://fsapartners ed gov/knowledge-center/library/dearcolleague-letters/2024-06-12/ability-benefit-state-processand-eligible-career-pathway-programs
► (GEN-24-151) Applying for Title IV Approval of an Eligible
Career Pathway Program for Ability to Benefit
This electronic announcement provides a reminder and
update for Title IV-eligible institutions applying for approval
of ECPPs for use with ATB 
https://fsapartners ed gov/fsa-print/publication/1006391
► DEAL Project Webpage
This page will house all DEAL project resources,
including recorded webinars and future technical
assistance tools 
https://cte ed gov/initiatives/dual-enrollment-adultlearners
► National College Transition Network Resource Page
This site developed by the National College Transition
Network includes links to additional resources on ATB,
career pathways, and state defined processes 
https://www collegetransition org/careerpathways/featured-projects/ability-to-benefit/resourcepage/
17
Overview of TA Opportunity
Presenters: Sandy Goodman and Alexis Cherewka, World Education
18
DEAL TA Opportunities
TA to State Teams
(including Postsecondary
Institutions)
TA to Postsecondary
Institutions
19
TA to State Teams
Designed for 4-6 state teams interested in developing a state process 
Teams will receive support from subject matter experts and project
advisors and engage in peer learning and sharing opportunities 
20
TA Objectives
TA will help state teams achieve the following objectives:
• Increase their knowledge of the state process option, the
application process, and related requirements 
• Explore examples of currently approved state processes 
• Determine state priorities, processes, and requirements for a
state-defined process 
• Develop a state process that builds and leverages (1) intentional
and sustained systems, (2) clear and collaborative partnerships,
and (3) a learner-centered mindset 
21
State Team Composition
• Adult Education State Director (or designee)
• Career and Technical Education (CTE) State Director (or designee)
• Director of state’s community and technical college system (or
designee)
• State agency staff member who has responsibility and/or knowledge
of federal student aid (or designee)
• Representatives from 1-2 community or technical college(s) with
ATB experience (e g , director of financial aid and directors of adult
education/career pathway initiatives)
22
State TA Activities & Timeline
Timeframe: June to December 2025
Activity Dates Description Level of Effort
Cohort
Sessions
Session 1:
6/26/25, 2:30-4:00pm
Session 2:
7/24/25, 2:30-4:00pm
Session 3:
8/21/25, 2:30-4:00pm
Session 4:
9/25/25, 2:30-4:00pm
• Four virtual session to review federal
requirements, successful state models,
promising practices and innovations, and
common challenges 
• Each session will include facilitated team
planning time and joint activities 
• NOTE: In between each session, state team
will meet with assigned SME/TA provider to
(1) debrief, (2) address questions and
challenges, and (3) develop an action plan 
Approx  4-6 hours
per month
Individualized
TA Sessions
October to December
2025
• States will work with assigned SME to (1)
implement action plan and (2) develop a
state-defined process 
Approx  4-6 hours
per month
23
Participation Expectations
• At least two members of the team should attend all virtual cohort
sessions:
• The team lead (as designated in the application) – required for all sessions
• The most relevant team member(s) based on the content of the TA activities
• All team members should participate in the following activities:
• Team meetings between virtual cohort sessions
• Development and implementation of team action plan
• Individual TA sessions
24
TA to Postsecondary Institutions
Designed for postsecondary institutions from state teams interested
in scaling their own ATB usage will receive support from subject
matter experts and project advisors and engage in peer learning and
sharing opportunities 
25
TA Objectives (2)
TA will help postsecondary institutions achieve the following
objectives:
• Increase awareness of successful models of ATB usage
• Integrate ATB usage into their integrated education and training
(IET) programs and career pathway initiatives
• Utilize promising practices and challenge
• Leverage their state-defined process to increase usage of all ATB
methods
• Complete the ECPP approval process
26
College TA Activities & Timeline
Timeframe: October 2025 to March 2026
Activity Dates Description Level of Effort
Cohort
Sessions
October 2025–
February 2026
• Three virtual session to review federal and state
requirements for an institution to have a career
