About ATB
Presenters: Sandy Goodman and Alexis Cherewka, World Education
7
What is ATB?
ATB alternatives allow students who do not have a high school
diploma or equivalency to become eligible for Title IV student
assistance (federal student aid) if the student is enrolled in an eligible
career pathway program (ECPP) 
8
ATB Timeline
9
ATB Student Eligibility
• Students who seek Title IV eligibility under ATB alternatives, must:
• Be enrolled in an ECPP
• Have the opportunity to attain a high school equivalency -
underscoring the importance of dual enrollment in both adult
education and the postsecondary career pathway
• Be eligible for federal student aid
Note: Paraphrased from (GEN-24-08) Ability to Benefit State Process and Eligible Career Pathways Programs, Dear
Colleague Letter, June 12, 2024
10
ATB Student Eligibility (continued)
• Students must also meet one of the following ATB eligibility
alternatives:
• Pass an ATB test (CELSA, ACCUPLACER, Texas Success Initiative
Assessment)
• Complete at least six credit hours or 225 clock hours applicable to
a degree or certificate offered by the postsecondary institution
• Participate in a state process approved by the Secretary of
Education
Note: Paraphrased from (GEN-24-08) Ability to Benefit State Process and Eligible Career Pathways Programs, Dear
Colleague Letter, June 12, 2024
11
ECPPs
• Students must be concurrently enrolled in all three of the following:
• Adult education and literacy programming that assists adults in
attaining a high school diploma or equivalent,
• A Title IV eligible postsecondary program, and
• Workforce preparation activities and training for a specific
occupation or occupational cluster 
Note: Paraphrased from (GEN-24-08) Ability to Benefit State Process and Eligible Career Pathways Programs, Dear
Colleague Letter, June 12, 2024
12
ECPPs (continued)
• ECPPs must also:
• Align with the skill needs of the state or regional economy
• Include academic and career counseling
• Accelerate students’ educational and career advancement
Note: Paraphrased from (GEN-24-08) Ability to Benefit State Process and Eligible Career Pathways Programs, Dear
Colleague Letter, June 12, 2024
13
Why Implement a State Process?
• Students don’t have to wait until they can pass a test or earn six
credits 
• Students and colleges don’t have to find funds for test fees or the
first six credits 
• State processes can help create and support an intentional adult
dual enrollment strategy 
• States don’t have to commit all institutions to implementing the state
process when applying 
• Colleges in states with an approved process have more options – they can also use other two ATB options (i e , states and institutions
are not limited to one ATB alternative) 
14
States with Approved State Processes
● California
● Illinois
● Iowa
● Minnesota
● Mississippi
● Washington
● Wisconsin
States that have or recently had an approved state process 
15
Promising Practices of Adopters
A landscape scan identified three interconnected themes of adopters
and their partners:
• Intentional and sustained systems that allows adopters to
effectively identify, enroll, support, and track both potential and
current ATB students 
• Clear and collaborative partnerships that are driven by a shared
vision and sense of collective responsibility 
• A learner-centered mindset driven by the belief that adult
learners can succeed in postsecondary education without a high
school equivalency 
